y -- tAbout the Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLand, Value, Community provides an in-depth critical study of the theories of J. Baird Callicott, one of the world's foremost environmental philosophers. An international group of scholars representing philosophy, ecology, ecofeminism, Native American studies, political science, and religion studies critically assesses Callicott's contributions to environmental ethics and philosophy and presents alternative perspectives from their own work. Each section consists of several authors focusing on one aspect of Callicott's thought, raising questions not only for Callicott but also for anyone affected by environmental issues. A noteworthy feature of the book is Callicott's own response to his critics. This volume allows readers to explore multiple avenues in their search for answers to the significant philosophical questions raised by environmental problems.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aHuman ecologyxPhilosophy. 4aEnvironmental Studies : Ecology. 7aSCIENCE / Environmental Science (see also Chemistry / Environmental).2bisacsh1 aBarkdull, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBooth, Annie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBratton, Susan Power, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCallicott, J. Baird, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCheney, Jim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDonner, Wendy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGruen, Lori, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHargrove, Eugene C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/voc